HOUSE JOINT RESOLUTION 1150
By Chism
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Reverend Jesse L.
Jackson, Sr.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of Reverend Jesse L. Jackson, Sr.; and
WHEREAS, Reverend Jesse Jackson was a towering leader in the fight for civil rights,
voting rights, and human dignity across the United States and around the world; and
WHEREAS, Reverend Jackson was born on October 8, 1941, in Greenville, South
Carolina, where his early life experiences helped shape the faith, resilience, and commitment to
justice that would define his lifelong work; and
WHEREAS, Reverend Jesse Jackson's extraordinary leadership spanned three defining
eras of American life—the Jim Crow period, the civil rights era, and the post-civil rights era—
during which he remained a relentless and principled voice for dignity, hope, and progress; and
WHEREAS, through visionary leadership and the founding of the Rainbow PUSH
Coalition, Reverend Jackson mobilized communities, expanded civic participation, and helped
register and turn out voters on a scale that strengthened American democracy; and
WHEREAS, Reverend Jesse Jackson's work as an international diplomat and human
rights advocate elevated the global struggle for freedom and justice, including his steadfast
opposition to apartheid and his advocacy on behalf of oppressed people worldwide; and
WHEREAS, for decades, Reverend Jackson was a trusted friend to the National Black
Caucus of State Legislators and a distinguished recipient of the organization's highest honor,
the Nation Builder Award, recognizing a lifetime dedicated to expanding justice, strengthening
democracy, and advancing opportunity for Black communities and marginalized people; and
WHEREAS, Reverend Jesse Jackson inspired generations of public servants, and for
HJR1150
014584
- 1 -

state legislators across the nation, he embodied the unwavering belief that progress is always
possible; and
WHEREAS, his enduring call to the nation, "Keep hope alive," continues to motivate
leaders, communities, and future generations to pursue equity, justice, and opportunity for all;
and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE ONE HUNDRED
FOURTEENTH GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE SENATE
CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of Reverend Jesse L. Jackson, Sr., reflecting fondly
upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the examined life with
courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Reverend Jackson.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
